That's two delta columns which gets wide. Alternatively, just show MTD vs. Prior Month Final and note the day count in the header (e.g. "Through Day 14 of 30"). A GM immediately knows if they're on pace. That's my recommendation ‚Äî one column, most actionable.

On Multi-Dealership Layout
Stacking per-store metric blocks works but gets long fast ‚Äî three stores √ó 5 inbound metrics = 15 rows just for inbound, and a GM has to scroll up and down to compare stores. A few alternatives worth considering:
Option A ‚Äî Stores as columns (my recommendation)
Metrics are rows, each store is a column. One table, everything visible at once. Easy to compare Mustang Ford vs. Alligator Audi side by side on the same metric.
METRICMUSTANG FORDALLIGATOR AUDIDOWNTOWN CHEVUnique Connected Opps312287341Unique Appts Set114 (40% hard)98 (35% hard)127 (44% hard)Total Appt Set Rate41%38%43%Delighted Customers89 (23%)71 (19%)94 (25%)Disappointed Customers31 (8%)44 (12%)28 (7%)
A GM can instantly see which store is leading and which needs attention. Add a thin "pace" indicator or light green/red shading on the best/worst value per row and it becomes a true performance dashboard.
Option B ‚Äî Stacked store blocks (what you described)
Better if each store's GM gets their own copy of the alert with just their store's data. The multi-store view stacked is really for a dealer group operator, not a store-level GM.
Option C ‚Äî Scorecard with rank
Stores as rows, metrics as columns, with a rank badge (1st/2nd/3rd) on each row. Very compact, very competitive. Works well if your GM audience responds to competition between stores.

My recommendation: Use Option A (stores as columns) for a dealer group view, and produce a separate per-store version for individual GMs that just shows their store plus an anonymized benchmark (e.g. "Group Avg"). That's a product differentiator ‚Äî two alert variants from one data pull.
